   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_parser.c:1365-1378`
   (`class_static_assignment_expr`) emits the static initializer assignment
   after parsing the right-hand expression. For declarations like `class B:A
   static a=A ... static c=A end`, the parser copies the class expression `e`
   and later calls `be_code_member()`/`be_code_setvar()` to assign `B.a = A`.
   During RHS parsing and member packaging, temporary registers are allocated,
   but this path does not preserve/release the class object expression correctly
   across repeated static initializers in a class body. The observed debugger
   state shows the compiler raising `tests/class_const.be:97: register overflow
   (more than 255)` from `be_code_setvar()` while compiling a static
   initializer, meaning `finfo->freereg` has grown to `0xff`. The bad code
   generation path leaks temporary registers for class static assignments, so
   valid class constants in subclasses are compiled incorrectly and the test
   oracle fails even though the process exits normally.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Ensure the temporary register(s) used to build the member
   assignment for a class static initializer are released after emitting the
   assignment. Minimal fix in `class_static_assignment_expr`:
   
   ```diff
    static void class_static_assignment_expr(bparser *parser, bexpdesc *e, bstring *name)
    {
